TopicTitle: The Ui Flicker Bug - In stock

Articles.Content:
Dear squaddies

ive got stock and modded installs of 1.2 etc but i think ive maybe found a stock bug, but can only prove it by adding mods, so advice needed is 'where do i go from here' ?

weve put up a thread in modded support, which hasnt been looked at or i should say commented on by squad (will provide link when i edit) 

edit - link : 

 

it seems, certainly not proven (still testing etc) that when a parts category gets too full, a strange UI bug rears its head.

it doesnt happen in just stock and it doesnt happen when ive tried running ksp with each mod i use 'on its own', obviously all my mods are for 1.2 etc and i only use reputable developers mods (cut down on the random factor) logs dont show anything major.

i can have 57-60 parts in category, any more and UI bug appears and it seems the more you have the worse it gets.

so, without installing mods, how can i show that stock MAY have a bug with amount of parts installed ?

Can i get an answer from squad before a mod moves this please

cheers

OH and ill keep bumping this up the thread til its solved or w.i.p. 

Edited October 16, 2016 by Tr1gg3r
To provide link
If you have mods, it's almost certainly a mod bug. Suggest you head over the the modded installs section

Weve already got thread over there mate and its not clear its mod issue.....yet

cheers for reply tho, thought i was invisible

Morning,

still no advice then, theres alot of people affected with this bug, whether it be stock or modded issue, theres alot of consumers taking time and trying to help and provide info to get to the cause of it. 

Im surprised there isnt a procedure in place to follow to check these border line issues..... Ive seen mention of using MM patches to replicate stock parts in order to check, sounds great idea to me, our reply was - lets make sure its a stock or modded issue first......YES BUT HOW.! 

Weve wasted our time trying every different combo we could think of, doing your work, we ask for help/ advice (nothing) i'll send ya invoice for my hourly rate shall i ? As it far outweighs hours actually playing the game.

Now im getting annoyed.....so im gonna finish here, same old squad silence, i can understand others' frustrations better now.

If we want support weve got to jump thru hoops include all info....attach this and that and get berated if its wrong... So why arent you helping us to help you? Weve asked what you want us to do, so we can help better, provide better info.

well, no more peeps, sort ur own game out.....id like to see how well youd all do, if the community didnt help with bug reporting etc.

im out.

edit - I was going to shut this thread down...... However i was asked to keep open as LeLeon has done some great work testing and provided more info for you. 

Nice one LeLeon, ill be watching from afar. I'll change thread title when ive worked out how to do it

 

Edited October 16, 2016 by Tr1gg3r
LeLeon has more info

13 hours ago, DuoDex said:

If you have mods, it's almost certainly a mod bug. Suggest you head over the the modded installs section

i reproduced it with stock part configs.

stock + 100 parts: I duplicated 100 times a tank -> start game, Build a PDD-12 Copula in VAB -> click every category and start hover over items randomly -> No Flicker

stock + 200 parts: I duplicated additional 100 times a science part -> start game -> build a PDD-12 Copula in VAB -> click every category and start hover over items randomly -> No Flicker

stock + 300 parts: I duplicated additional 100 times a wheel part -> start game -> build a PDD-12 Copula in VAB -> click every category and start hover over items randomly -> Flicker

stock + 300 parts: i switched the 100 wheel part to a 100 utility part -> start game -> build a PDD-12 Copula in VAB -> click every category and start hover over items randomly -> Flicker

For some reasons when i hovered on 300 files flicker conditions over the items in energy category i had UI freezes. seen on the video.

Hookay everybody, let's take a bit of a chill pill here.

@RoverDude knows about the issue. There's no point getting all worked up about semantics.

Emotions are flaring because RoverDude is trying to be precise about terminology so the right people can look at the right stuff to fix it. If we call it a stock bug, it may well go to an entirely different developer or department, who will simply run their stock test install, say "nope, can't reproduce" and that's that. On the players' side, however, his response can feel almost flippant, because to us we're reading into it "Nope, it's not stock, so it's not a stock problem, so go suck a pickle."

It's pretty clear at this point, that that isn't what he's saying at all.

To me, given that he's the author of one of the most popular part-heavy mod packages in the game, and thus has an inherent vested interest in solving this, so his own passionate work can be enjoyed, it was always clear that it wasn't what he was saying, but... maybe that's just me.

Also, as he said, it's the weekend. Not only that, it's the first weekend after a major update. In other words, these people have spent the last several weeks (months?) working 80 hour weeks, sacrificing nights, weekends, time with their families, and their own hobbies, to get 1.2 out at all. I'm surprised anyone has bothered to respond yet this weekend, and I applaud RoverDude for doing so. And... also look at him slightly strangely, as I sure as hell wouldn't have in his place. XD

So maybe multiple bumps in a matter of hours on a Saturday afternoon is just a tad excessive?

If you're really bothered by this issue, you have three (wise) choices here:

  1. Live with it.
  2. Go play another game, watch some TV, or engage in another hobby for a few days/weeks until the bug is tracked down and fixed. It's not a betrayal or anything to do other things. (I typically leave KSP for months at a time whenever a new update comes 'round and breaks all my beloved mods, then come back when everything is all stable and mature again. 1.2 was atypical of me, because the pre-release really wowed me with the features they'd added to the stock game, and I wanted to explore them, and was also curious to see what I could do without any of the crutches I've come to rely on. And I'm rather proud that I submitted a couple of bugs that actually got fixed, that nobody else had found. *beams*)
  3. Reduce your part-heavy mod count temporarily to the ones you -truly- want and need for the current projects you're working on in-game, then wait until it's resolved to add the peripheral parts mods back in.

Aaaand, that's it. Anything else at this point, including piling on without adding more relevant information, is just wasting time and energy, yours and theirs.
